Title : St Justinian
Text : [[File:Access steps to the harbour at St Justinian - geograph.org.uk - 1517036.jpg|The steps down to St Justinian harbour|right|thumb]]
[[File:St Justinian's chapel - geograph.org.uk - 739871.jpg|The ruined chapel of St Justinian | right | thumb]]
'''St Justinian''' (or '''St Justinian's'''<ref>Note that the [[Ordnance Survey]] uses both "St Justinian" and "St Justinian's" on different maps: [http://www.bing.com/maps/?mkt=en-gb&v=2&cp=51.877778~-5.31&lvl=14&sp=Point.51.877778_-5.31_St%20Justinian%27s&sty=s here (1:25,000)] and [http://www.bing.com/maps/?mkt=en-gb&v=2&cp=51.877778~-5.31&lvl=14&sp=Point.51.877778_-5.31_St%20Justinian%27s&sty=s here (1:50,000)]</ref> or '''St Justinians''') is a coastal location in [[Pembrokeshire]], Wales, in the [[community (Wales)|community]] of [[St Davids and the Cathedral Close]]. It is named for [[Justinian of Ramsey Island]]. There is a small harbour housing the [[St Davids Lifeboat Station]], and a private residence. The harbour is used for boat trips to [[Ramsey Island]], and for kayaking and speedboat trips.  It is a popular access point for the [[Pembrokeshire Coastal Path]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pembrokeshirecoast.org.uk/?PID=135|title=Parking at St Justinian|publisher=Pembrokeshire Coast National Park|accessdate=24 April 2014 |quote=}}</ref>

The ruined chapel of St Justinian is nearby and is a Grade I [[listed building]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wa-12692-ruins-of-st-justinian-s-chapel-porthstini|title=Ruins of St.justinian's Chapel,porthstinian/ St.justinian's, St David's and the Cathedral Close|publisher=British Listed Buildings|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref>  The 1870s old lifeboat house,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wa-12696-old-lifeboat-house-porthstinian-st-justin|title=Old Lifeboat House,porthstinian/St.justinian's, St David's and the Cathedral Close|publisher=British Listed Buildings|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref> 1911 lifeboat house,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wa-12695-lifeboat-house-porthstinian-st-justinian-|title=Lifeboat House,porthstinian/St.justinian's, St David's and the Cathedral Close|publisher=British Listed Buildings|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref> St Justinian's Well (19th century over an ancient spring), and an early 20th century watchtower<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wa-12694-watch-tower-to-nw-of-st-justinian-s-porth|title=Watch Tower to Nw.of St.justinian's, Porthstinian/St.justinian's, St David's and the Cathedral Close|publisher=British Listed Buildings|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref> are all Grade II listed buildings.

The bay on which St Justinian stands is known as Porthstinian.<ref>Shown on Ordnance Survey maps.</ref>

